{
  "text": "The lateral hypothalamus (LH) has been thought to play a critical role in sleep-wake regulation since the early studies of Von Economo (1930) . Lesions and acute inhibition of LH neurons are known to increase sleep time (Ranson, 1939; Nauta, 1946; de Ryck and Teitelbaum, 1978; Shoham and Teitelbaum, 1982; [CITATION_1] while excitation produces arousal and increases in activity [CITATION_2] Sinnamon et al., 1999; [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Several studies have identified wake-active neurons in the LH [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] , but their neurochemical identity is unknown. More recently, inhibitory LH neuronal populations have been identified that induce wakefulness on optogenetic or chemogenetic stimulation [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] . The wakepromoting LH cell population that has been studied most extensively to date are the hypocretin/orexin (Hcrt) neurons [CITATION_10] [CITATION_11] Kilduff and Peyron, 2000; Bonnavion and de Lecea, 2010) . These cells project to several wakepromoting areas of the brain including the basal forebrain (BF), the tuberomamillary nucleus (TMN), and the locus coeruleus (LC), where they can release the Hcrt peptides, glutamate, dynorphin, and perhaps other neurotransmitters [CITATION_12] [CITATION_13] Sch\u00f6ne et al., 2012 Sch\u00f6ne et al., , 2014 . In this regard, the Hcrt neurons have been proposed to act like a stabilizer of a flip-flop switch that controls behavioral state [CITATION_14] .",
